\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now include a superconductivity proximity effects by including an
 constant pairing 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta(x)\equiv\Delta_{0}$
\end_inset

 which can be achieved by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=0$
\end_inset

, as illustrated in Fig.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{fig:infSCnw}}$
\end_inset

).
 In this case the Hamiltonian reads as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{\mathcal{H}}_{\text{BdG}}\left(\Delta(x)=\Delta_{0}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{cc|cc}
\eta k^{2}-\mu & V_{\text{Z}}+i\alpha_{\text{R}}k & \Delta_{0} & 0\\
V_{\text{Z}}-i\alpha_{\text{R}}k & \eta k^{2}-\mu & 0 & \Delta_{0}\\
\hline \Delta_{0} & 0 & -\eta k^{2}+\mu & V_{\text{Z}}-i\alpha_{\text{R}}k\\
0 & \Delta_{0} & V_{\text{Z}}+i\alpha_{\text{R}}k & -\eta k^{2}+\mu
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset

One again, we can make the ansatz of a plane-wave solution 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{ikx}\Psi$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 being the momentum along a sufficient large wire.

\color blue
 
\color inherit
The energy-momentum band dispersion follows trivially as the characteristic
 equation solution,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E_{\pm}^{2}(k)=\left(\eta k^{2}-\mu\right)^{2}+\alpha_{\text{R}}^{2}k^{2}+V_{\text{Z}}^{2}+\Delta_{0}^{2}\pm2\sqrt{\left(\eta k^{2}-\mu\right)^{2}\left(\alpha_{\text{R}}^{2}k^{2}+V_{\text{Z}}^{2}\right)+V_{\text{Z}}^{2}\Delta_{0}^{2}},\label{eq:Ean}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

having now four solution, two for the electron 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{e\pm}$
\end_inset

 and two for the electron-hole 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{h\pm}$
\end_inset

, related as 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{e\pm}=-E_{h\pm}$
\end_inset

 due to time-reversed symmetry.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Fig.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{fig:Ean}}$
\end_inset

) we show how the spectrum behaves as one tunes the quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{Z}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Also, note that tweaking with the effective mass 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta=\nicefrac{\hbar²}{2m^{*}}$
\end_inset

 only results in the horizontal squishing of the spectrum.
 The pairing will play two crucial roles: opening a gap at the outer wings
 of the dispersion, near the Fermi momenta 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{\text{F}}$
\end_inset

 
\color blue
why is it the Fermi wave vector?
\color inherit
 corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\eta k_{\text{F}}^{2}-\mu\right)\pm\alpha_{\text{R}}k_{\text{F}}=0$
\end_inset


\color blue
 
\color inherit
where the Zeeman field is unimportant (often called 
\emph on
minigap
\emph default
, although it can actually be bigger than the 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0$
\end_inset

 gap for certain values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{Z}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{0}$
\end_inset

; thus, for the sake of labeling them, we shall use the terminology gap
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0$
\end_inset

 and minigap for 
\begin_inset Formula $k=k_{\text{F}}$
\end_inset

) and modifying the gap forming near 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\color purple
The former role eliminates the possibility of high-momentum gapless excitations,
 thus leaving only the chiral states near 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0$
\end_inset

 as low energy excitation.

\color inherit
 The latter role allows us to tune the topological phase transitions.

\color purple
 We note that there is another way for gapping out the large momentum excitation
s, for example, by coupling our system to an antiferromagnet with periodicity
 comparable to 
\begin_inset Formula $2k_{F}$
\end_inset

 of the wire.
 Interactions may also open a superconductive minigap for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

's away from the Zeeman gap.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Furthermore, see that for 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0$
\end_inset

 the analytical expression of the spectrum reduces to 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\pm}^{2}(0)=\left(V_{\text{Z}}\pm V_{C}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{C}=\sqrt{\mu^{2}+\Delta_{0}^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 At the critical point when 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{Z}}=V_{C}$
\end_inset

 the gap actually closes.
 It's this closing and opening of bands that indicates the transition to
 a different topological regime, as shown in Fig.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{fig:Ean}}$
\end_inset

)(*).
 For values 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{Z}}<V_{C}$
\end_inset

 the nanowire is in it's trivial phase and has a superconducting gap 
\color purple
(being no longer spinless)
\color inherit
 while for values 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{Z}}>V_{C}$
\end_inset

 the nanowire is in it's topological phase, having a spin gap due to the
 Zeeman field or SO effects.
 Note, however, that the minigap will be always a superconducting gap.
 Of course, having set a pairing potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{0}$
\end_inset

, one can achieve this phase transition by either tuning directly the Zeeman
 field 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{Z}}$
\end_inset

 and/or the chemical potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

.
 The various tuning scenarios can be understood by analyzing the extensive
 examples in Fig.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{fig:Ean}}$
\end_inset

).
 For example, and looking at the spectrums in the topological phase transition
 (depicted in yellow), we see that the role of the SO coupling is crucial;
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{\text{R}}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{Z}}>\Delta_{0}$
\end_inset

 the spectrum is gapless because the magnetic field is basically destroying
 the superconductivity however when setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{\text{R}}>0$
\end_inset

 we see the emergence of a topological minigap to emerge at 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{Z}}=V_{C}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

