\begin_layout Standard
Moreover, let us now consider the limiting case of a the spin-
\begin_inset Formula $1/2$
\end_inset

 repulsive Hubbard model where 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{ij}=U\delta_{ij}$
\end_inset

.
 The mean field decoupling then gives rise to just an onsite term that leads
 to magnetism
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{i}^{U}=U\left(\frac{1}{2}\text{Tr}\left(\tau_{z}\tilde{\boldsymbol{\rho}}_{i}\right)\left[\tau_{z}\otimes\sigma_{0}\right]-\tilde{\boldsymbol{\rho}}_{i}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The effective onsite potential 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is usually taken as 
\begin_inset Formula $U>0$
\end_inset

 in order to describe the onsite repulsive Coulomb potential between the
 electrons however, there are several mechanisms (e.g in the BCS case through
 the coupling of the electrons with the lattice) which can induce an effective
 attraction among the electrons which overcomes the repulsive electromagnetic
 interaction resulting in a 
\begin_inset Formula $U<0$
\end_inset

.
 So, for example, with half-filled bands (which in our Majorana wire system
 corresponds to setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=2t$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $2t-\mu=0$
\end_inset

), by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $U>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=0$
\end_inset

 our system should behave as a ferromagnet in the equilibrium state, having
 all of the spin oriented in the same direction (as a side note, one must
 set 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{Z}}\neq0$
\end_inset

 such that the system can either spontaneously pick either the up or down
 direction, or else the system will oscillates between those states and
 never converge).
 Let us assume that the system spontaneously picks the up direction.
 Then we must obtain equal purely electronic 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{i\uparrow\uparrow}^{\text{ee}}$
\end_inset

 and purely holeonic 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{i\downarrow\downarrow}^{\text{hh}}$
\end_inset

 due to electron-hole symmetry, this two together amounting to a total charge
 of two, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{i\uparrow\uparrow}^{\text{ee}}=\rho_{i\downarrow\downarrow}^{\text{hh}}=1$
\end_inset

.
 The fact that the total charge amounts to two is true independent of filling
 (for 
\begin_inset Formula $U>0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=0$
\end_inset

 still), 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\rho}_{i}$
\end_inset

's diagonal would just read instead as 
\begin_inset Formula $(\rho_{i\uparrow\uparrow}^{\text{ee}},\,\rho_{i\uparrow\uparrow}^{\text{ee}},\,1-\rho_{i\uparrow\uparrow}^{\text{ee}},\,1-\rho_{i\uparrow\uparrow}^{\text{ee}})$
\end_inset

.
